{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59da49ff-c605-4093-986a-f49003aa2551","content":"Your project is already set up with the HotReload extension. Here's how to use it:\n\n**Run tests in hot-reload mode:**\n\n```\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis keeps the test host running and watches for file changes. When you save edits to your test or source files, it automatically re-runs the affected tests — no full rebuild needed.\n\n**Your current issue:** `IsValidEmail` only checks for non-empty strings but doesn't validate the `@` sign, so `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` will fail. With hot reload running, you can fix `IsValidEmail` and see results instantly on save.\n\nWant me to start it up and fix the failing test?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"63b9f528-da30-4fa8-8167-52e525d513a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a test project with `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` already referenced. They want to know how to use it for quick iteration.\n\nLet me explain how to use the hot reload testing feature. The key is to run `dotnet test` with the `--hotreload` flag (or use `dotnet watch test`). Actually, let me think about this more carefully.\n\nWith `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload`, you use `dotnet test --hotreload` which keeps the test host running and watches for file changes. When you save a file, it automatically re-runs the tests without a full rebuild.\n\n\nI'll start by running the tests to show what we're working with, then walk through the hot reload workflow.","outputTokens":342,"requestId":"1BCA:13C87:DA46CF:F7D457:6A03DA55"},"id":"b7ec0cac-d5d7-4719-bae8-5ff9e0f5fc1b","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:56:46.500Z","parentId":"2e99c73f-229f-4829-bde2-2a61a748684e"}
